 :tx/rationale "UAQ INSIGHT 17: HEBBIAN-BAYESIAN DYNAMICS — PRECISE FORMULAS. The connection lifecycle requires three concrete computations: \n\nHEBBIAN CO-ACTIVATION BOOST: When entities A and B are activated in the same context, their connection gets boost = proximity_weight * activation_strength. Proximity weights: same_command = 1.0 (agent's action directly references both), same_session = 0.5 (both activated within one session but different commands), adjacent_session = 0.25 (activated in consecutive sessions). Accumulation: hebbian_boost += boost. Decay: hebbian_boost *= 0.5 per session (half-life). This is already the ATT-2 Hebbian model, now generalized to all connection types.\n\nBAYESIAN POSTERIOR CONFIDENCE: When a connection prediction is tested (agent confirms or rejects a proposed edge), update confidence: posterior = (prior * likelihood) / evidence. In practice: confidence = confirmed_count / (confirmed_count + rejected_count + smoothing). Smoothing = 2.0 (Laplace prior, prevents extreme confidence from small samples). After 8 confirmations and 2 rejections with smoothing=2: confidence = 10/14 = 0.71. This is already the hypothesis ledger's calibration model, now generalized.\n\nTEMPORAL DECAY: Connections not activated decay geometrically: confidence *= decay_rate^sessions_since_last_activation. decay_rate = 0.9. After 5 sessions without activation: 0.9^5 = 0.59 of original confidence. After 10: 0.9^10 = 0.35. After 20: 0.9^20 = 0.12. Entity-change signal: if the SOURCE or TARGET entity receives new datoms, all connections FROM/TO that entity get accelerated decay (decay_rate = 0.7 instead of 0.9) until re-verified.\n\nCOMBINED: effective_weight = bayesian_confidence * temporal_decay * (1 + hebbian_boost). The hebbian_boost is additive (can exceed 1.0 for strongly co-activated connections), while confidence and decay are multiplicative gates. This is the learned_weight in the attention schema.\n\nSPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-029, ADR-FOUNDATION-024. FILE: These formulas belong in a new connection_dynamics() function, likely in methodology.rs or a new connections.rs module."
